refusal to treat particular populations","Deliberate preference for certain cultural practices","Unconscious attitudes that influence clinical decisions","Intentional selection of preferred patient demographics"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnconscious attitudes that influence clinical decisions\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes implicit bias. These are unintentional and unconscious beliefs or attitudes that affect how healthcare providers interact with and treat patients from different backgrounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConscious discrimination against specific patient groups\u003C/strong\u003E represents explicit bias where providers knowingly discriminate against certain populations.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExplicit refusal to treat particular populations\u003C/strong\u003E describes overt and intentional discrimination rather than unconscious bias.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeliberate preference for certain cultural practices\u003C/strong\u003E indicates conscious cultural preferences rather than unconscious attitudes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntentional selection of preferred patient demographics\u003C/strong\u003E describes conscious patient selection practices rather than unconscious biases.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding implicit bias is crucial because it can contribute to healthcare disparities even when providers have explicit commitments to equality and fairness. Recognition of these unconscious biases is essential for improving healthcare delivery to all populations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Implicit bias is defined as unconscious attitudes and stereotypes that affect one\u0027s understanding, actions, and decisions.","Healthcare provider implicit bias can contribute to racial and ethnic disparities in healthcare delivery and outcomes.","Recognition of implicit bias is the critical first step in attempt to mitigate the impact of implicit bias on clinical decision-making."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53710"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17013"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53710"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T15:33:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T15:34:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9703"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68253"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty